demand: How individuals act within an economy, when having to decide who gets how much money. Individual's (cultural/educational) background, nationality, political party, age etc. affect one's market/decision making behaviour.
comment: I liked this one. Immediately once I got the instructions, I started to think of a way in which I could gain the most money. I realised even before thinking, that wanting to keep all the money to myself would not be the answer as being too selfish will not get you anywhere in the market. No one else would not have accepted my offer.
degree: BA in Business Management and Modern Languages

demand: How much people are willing to share with other people based on how similar/different they are to them - how judgmental people can be with some identity hidden
comment: Quite lengthy and repetitive - every round gave near enough equal amounts of money. Good way of testing how people view equality if that was the aim.

demand: How, regardless of the political orientation of the participants, the money is divided. May be the capacity to share of people, even when you do not expect it.
comment: People tends to share more than I imagined, and I need to become a more sharing person, even when I feel I would need more money.

demand: Economy and psychology. Risk taking. Consistency between the behavior and the declared political opinions of the participants.

degree: English studies. Language and linguistic depart.

demand: I suppose it was about how we see those around us and to what extent we consider us all to be equal and deserving of the same resources. Only one other participant was needed to get an offer approved, so technically there was no need to also provide some money for the third participant. In that sense, it was also a test of our moral and approach to fairness.
comment: I was interesting to see the different offers and what it took for two people to reject it. How much are we willing to compromise and what can we let pass - quite interesting.
degree: BA Business Management and Modern Languages

demand: How people with left and right political views are willing to distribute money.And in general in the community how people want to distribute public money between themselves and others.
comment: Engaging, easier for people with economics or political studies but suitable for the general public as well.

demand: I thought it was about entering a business partnership and how money is dispatched. Usually the person that introduces the deal will get more than the others, and when an unfair deal is made everyone looks at how much he gains before rejecting the offer: "even if it is unfair to someone as long as it is not me i will accept the offer"
comment: It is well conducted though the blanks between each round is quite important. It seems interesting, i'd like to know more about that experiment.

demand: Monetary attribution in regards to political opinions
comment: It was rather interesting. I didn't think that there were that many socialists at university, i felt a bit alone as a conservative. another observation is that most off the times i would always be the one benefiting the max from the period.

demand: It was about seeing who is willing to give out what amount to each person but the strategy that most people used was to gain as much as possible but also giving the next person down enough to get them to accept the amount which would not be good for the odd one out

comment: That it is not easy to decide because from my personal point of view equal is great but it should be based on what people actually deserve

demand: How fair people are in sharing wealth.
comment: It was ok, a bit easy to cheat by placing in groups of 3, 2 people can share all the money and have majority vote leaving the third player with nothing.

demand: How people think money should be divided among a number of random people, including themselves. i.e whether it should be done equally or certain people should earn more
comment: I enjoyed it, and thought it was fun, i think there should have been a time limit though, as i was often waiting around for long time periods for the next round

demand: Decision making. Political peronsality:left or right
comment: It was interesting to take part in especially to see that each round was different. Hardly anyone thought alike

demand: I think the experiment was about working out that whether you were cutting your losses or not, and if you got more confident once winning or gaining more money as you went on. Whether the idea of money went to your head or not.
comment: I was impressed but I don't think you should have known before hand what ever you won you got to keep, because it led to people cutting a participant out of the money, in order to gain because if 2 people voted they got the money. But an interesting experiment as you never knew what you would get as it was like gambling.

demand: About how people make decisions in different situations. If you offered to someone a big quantity of money and the same for you it was accepted but the player number 3 wouldn't receive anything. I tried to divide the 17 pounds in more or less equal parts so everyone could earn something.
comment: That some people think like me but other prefer to earn as much as possible without caring if someone wouldn't receive anything

demand: About the principle we were told about on a lecture. Where we were told that people accept any positive amount even if it is very small because it will be profit anyway.
comment: I couldn't understand how the political views influence, maybe because i don't know the meaning of each. Too slowly, too much time for making a decision.
